    description:
      "Treasure Case 22.24The coin hoard was found while metal detecting on a small pasture field at a depth of 15 inches. The finder reported that 40 of the coins were found in the same hole and the remainder were scattered across the whole of the field (roughly an acre of land).&nbsp;Description of FindA hoard of Roman silver denarii dating to between 32 BC and AD 168. A summary list of the coins is below:\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tRuler\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tNo. of coins\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tMark Antony (coins dated 32-31 BC)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t2\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tNero (AD 54 &ndash; 68)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t2\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tOtho (AD 69)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tVespasian (AD 69-79)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t15\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp; Titus Caesar\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp; Domitian Caesar\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tTitus (AD 79-81)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp; Domitian Caesar\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tDomitian (AD 81-96)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t7\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tNerva (AD 96-8)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t4\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tTrajan (AD 98-117)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t24\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tHadrian (AD 117-38)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t17\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp;&nbsp; Sabina\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tAntoninus Pius (AD 138-61)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t9\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp;&nbsp; Diva Faustina I\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t3\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp;&nbsp; Marcus Caesar\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t2\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tMarcus Aurelius (AD 161-80)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t2\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp;&nbsp; Divus Pius\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp;&nbsp; Lucius Verus\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t2\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tTotal\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t96\t\t\t\t\t\tDiscussionThe composition of the hoard is consistent with other hoards of the period. The earliest coins are denarii of Mark Antony, struck at his travelling mint in 32-31 BC (RRC 544/8-39). The next coins in the hoard are of Nero (RIC I, 60 and 69), struck after his coin reforms of AD 64, which reduced the silver content of the denarius. Republican and imperial denarii struck before AD 64 do not usually appear in 2nd century coin hoards, because they were withdrawn from circulation during Trajan&rsquo;s reign (AD 98-117), when he initiated coin reforms himself. The hoard terminates with coins from the reign of Marcus Aurelius (AD 161- 180), the last coin of which was struck in AD 168 (RIC III, 191). These coins show very little use-wear suggesting that they had not been in circulation long before being buried. The findspot is quite isolated in terms of known Roman artefacts and sites. The closest site of significance is Carmarthen, the site of the Roman fort and town of Moridunum, approximately 10km to the Northwest. The hoard is the largest extant hoard of Roman denarii known to have been found in Carmarthenshire. Over 200 denarii were discovered in 1692 at Bronyscawen (IARCH-F9BC09), and a hoard of unknown size was found in the early 1800s in Llandeilo (IARCH-C14EF3). A hoard of gold aurei of Hadrian was found in the 1870s near Hermon (IARCH-5BE11E). The current location of these coin hoards is unknown. More recently a group of five denarii was discovered in Manordeilo and Salem Community in 2019-2020 (Treasure Case 21.09). The other Roman hoards known from Carmarthenshire are of later 3rd or 4th century date.",
