    notes:
      "Metal contentSilver denarii of this period typically contain greater than 80% silver by&nbsp;weight.&nbsp;Treasure Act considerationsAs two or more precious metal coins over 300 years old when found, these&nbsp;96 denarii qualify as Treasure if they were originally associated in the&nbsp;ground.&nbsp;All the coins represented in this group are known to have been in circulation&nbsp;at the same time and coin hoards with similar compositions have been found&nbsp;across England and Wales. The very close concentration of the coins&nbsp;indicates that they were deposited together. The scattered findspots of&nbsp;most of the coins suggests the hoard was disturbed by ploughing. On a&nbsp;balance of probability, it is likely that they were deposited together on a&nbsp;single occasion.RecommendationIt is my opinion that these coins qualify as Treasure under Section 1(1)(a)(ii)&nbsp;of the Treasure Act 1996 (see The Treasure Act 1996 Code of Practice (3rd&nbsp;Revision 2023), Section B. 11), because they were originally associated in the&nbsp;ground, contain more than ten per cent by weight of precious metal (silver),&nbsp;and are more than 300 years old when found.ReferencesIARCH &ndash; Iron Age and Roman Coin Hoards in Britain database number.RIC I &ndash; Sutherland, C.H.V., 1984 (Revised Edition), The Roman Imperial&nbsp;Coinage, Volume I, From 31 BC to AD 69, London; Spink and Son Ltd.&nbsp;RIC III &ndash; Mattingly, H. and Sydenham, E. A., 1930, The Roman Imperial&nbsp;Coinage, Volume III, Antoninus Pius to Commodus, London; Spink and Son&nbsp;Ltd.RRC &ndash; Crawford, M.H., 1974, Roman Republican Coinage, London; Cambridge&nbsp;University Press&nbsp;",
