    description:
      "Treasure Case 21.06Description of FindSeven Roman silver denarii, issued between 127 BC and AD 61.1.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Republican denarius issued by M. Caecilius Metellus, dating to 127 BC (Reece Period 1). Mint of Rome. RRC 263/1a.&nbsp;2.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Republican denarius issued by M. Aemilius Scaurus, dating to 58 BC (Reece Period 1). Mint of Rome. RRC 422/1a or 1b.&nbsp;3.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Denarius of Nero (AD 54-68), dating to AD 54 (Reece Period 3). Mint of Rome. RIC I (second edition) Nero 2.&nbsp;4.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Denarius of Nero (AD 54-68), dating to the period AD 59-61 (Reece Period 3). Mint of Rome. RIC I (second edition) Nero 20/22.&nbsp;5.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Incomplete denarius of Nero (AD 54-68), dating to the period AD 59-61 (Reece Period 3). Mint of Rome. RIC I (second edition) Nero 20/22.&nbsp;6.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;A fragment of a denarius of uncertain date.&nbsp;7.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;A fragment of a denarius of uncertain date.&nbsp;DiscussionThe Caersws I (Llwyn-y-brain) Roman fort is thought to be of early-Flavian date, predating the second fort at Caersws (also of Flavian date), which superseded it. The Fort was identified by aerial survey in 1956, which revealed ramparts and ditches visible as crop marks. A fieldwalking survey at the site in c. 1983 found early Roman material and a geophysical survey in 2007 discovered buildings within the ramparts (Davies 2007; 2010, 224-6; Dawson 1983).The coins are worn and corroded. All but two of the coins show damage from being in the plough soil. All five of the identifiable coins were struck before Nero&#39;s coin reforms of AD 64. The earliest of the coins are the most worn suggesting that they were in circulation for a longer period of time than the later coins. The two unidentifiable coins (coins 6 and 7) are the most worn of the group. This suggests that these two coins are of relatively early date compared to the least worn coins.&nbsp;",
