    notes:
      "Metal contentRoman denarii struck before Nero&rsquo;s coin reforms of AD 64 typically contain more than 93% silver by weight.Treasure Act considerationsAs two or more silver (&gt;10% Ag) coins over 300 years old when found, the seven coins discovered at Caersws Fort I qualify as Treasure if they were originally associated in the ground. The coins are types that would have circulated at the same time and were found close to each other. On balance of probability, the coins were deposited at the same time and then scattered by later ploughing.&nbsp;RecommendationIt is my opinion that these coins qualify as Treasure under Section 1(1)(a)(ii) of the Treasure Act 1996 (see The Treasure Act 1996 Code of Practice (3rd Revision 2023), Section B. 11 (DCMS 2023, 11)), because they were originally associated in the ground, contain more than ten per cent by weight of precious metal (silver), and are more than 300 years old when found.ReferencesDavies, J. L., 2010, &lsquo;Caersws I (Llwyn-y-brain)&rsquo;, in Burnham, B. C. and Davies, J. D. Roman (ed.), Frontiers in Wales and the Marches, Aberystwyth: Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales, 224-6.Davies, J. L., 2007, &lsquo;Llwyn y Brain (Caersws I)&rsquo;, Archaeology in Wales, 47, 145-6.&nbsp;Dawson, M. L., 1983, &lsquo;Llwyn Y Brain (Caersws I) Roman Fort&rsquo;, Archaeology in Wales, 23: 50.DCMS, 2023, Treasure Act 1996: Code of Practice (3rd Revision), London: Department for Culture, Media &amp; Sport.RIC &ndash; Sutherland, C. H. V. and Carson, R. A. G., The Roman Imperial Coinage Volume 1, Revised Edition, Augustus to Vitellus, London; Spink &amp; Son.RRC &ndash; Crawford, M. H., Roman Republican Coinage, London; Cambridge University Press.&nbsp;",
