    description:
      "Circumstances of discovery and reportingA hoard of 37 Roman silver coins was discovered by David Henry Moss and Tom Taylor on 20th-21st December 2018 and 19th January 2019 in Caerhun Community, Conwy.The coins were found while metal detecting on cultivated land that was under pasture at the time. The findspot (a National Grid Reference) of the coins and addresses of interested parties are given on the Treasure Receipt Form. The coins were discovered scattered in shallow rocky ploughsoil at depths of approximately 3-4 inches.Mr Moss and Mr Taylor discovered another coin hoard of Roman silver and copper alloy coins in a ceramic pot in an adjacent field (Treasure Case 19.01). They also discovered several Roman bronze artefacts in the same field and neighbouring fields. These artefacts were also handed in for reporting, but they were not considered to be part of the same find as the coin hoards and as such they are not considered to constitute potential Treasure. All the finds were deposited at Wrexham Museum on 7th January 2019 and then transferred to Amgueddfa Cymru on 18th January 2019 for report to H.M. Coroner for North Wales (East and Central) and for further investigation.Description of FindThe hoard consists of 37 Roman denarii dating from 32 BC to AD 221. Most of the coins date from the late 1st century AD to the end of the 2nd century AD. Four of the coins were struck at Mark Antony&rsquo;s travelling mint in 32-31 BC. The last coin in the hoard was struck in AD 221 during the reign of Elagabalus. A summary list of the coins is included at the end of this report.Local contextThe coin hoard was discovered near an apsidal structure which has previously been excavated and tentatively dated to the 3rd century AD.&nbsp;The metal detectorists who found this hoard also discovered a larger hoard of Roman denarii and radiates in a pot, probably buried around AD 270 (Treasure Case 19.01). Several Roman brooches and other artefacts were found in the vicinity. The hoards and artefacts are important supporting evidence for the identification of the building as a religious site and that it dates to the 3rd century. The findspot is around 2.5km North of Canovium Roman fort (NPRN 95640; PRN 662), an auxiliary 1st &ndash; 2nd century fort, which was reoccupied in the late-3rd to 4th century.DiscussionThe coins of Mark Antony&rsquo;s travelling mint contained less silver than contemporary coins, so they remained in circulation after Nero&rsquo;s coin reforms and the subsequent removal of pre-Neronian denarii from circulation. Their presence in a late denarius hoard like this is therefore not unusual. The last datable coin in the hoard is a denarius of Elagabalus&rsquo;s Series 4d (TR P IIII) which gives the hoard a terminus post quem (earliest possible date of deposition) of AD 221.&nbsp;Metal contentImperial silver denarii of the first to third century AD vary in fineness from greater than 90% silver by weight in the first century to about 50% silver in the early third century.Treasure Act considerationsAs two or more silver (&gt;10% Ag) coins over 300 years old when found, the 37 denarii qualify as Treasure if they were originally associated in the ground. All the coins represented in this group are known to have been in circulation at the same time. Coin hoards with similar compositions have been reported from across England and Wales. The earlier coins of the group, especially the denarii of Mark Antony and, to a lesser extent, the Flavian coins are more worn than the later coins, indicating that they had been in circulation for a long time when they were buried. The close concentration of coins is a good indication that they were deposited together, as is the lack of smaller denomination coins, which you would expect to be included among site finds. On a balance of probability, it is likely that they were deposited together on a single occasion.Summary list by ruler:\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tMark Antony (coins dated 32-31 BC)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t4\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tVespasian (AD 69-79)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t4\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp;&nbsp; Titus Caesar\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tTitus (AD 79-81)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tNerva (AD 96-8)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tTrajan (AD 98-117)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t3\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tHadrian (AD 117-38)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp;&nbsp; Sabina\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tAntoninus Pius (AD 138-61)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp;&nbsp; Diva Faustina I\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tMarcus Aurelius (AD 161-80)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t4\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp;&nbsp; Lucius Verus\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp;&nbsp; Faustina II under Marcus\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t4\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tCommodus (AD 180-192)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t2\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp;&nbsp; Divus Marcus\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tWars of the Succession (AD 193-198)\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp;\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp;&nbsp; Septimius Severus\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t2\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp;&nbsp; Julia Domna\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tElagabalus (AD 218-222)\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tUncertain Emperor\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t3\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tTotal\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t37",
