      "Treasure Act considerationsAs two or more silver (&gt;10% Ag) coins and ten or more copper alloy coins over 300 years old when found, the coins qualify as Treasure if they were originally associated in the ground. As the coins were contained in a ceramic vessel, they were clearly buried together at the same time.Recommendation&nbsp;It is my opinion that these coins and their ceramic container qualify as Treasure under Section 1(1)(a)(ii) of the Treasure Act 1996 (see The Treasure Act 1996 Code of Practice (2nd Revision 2003), paragraphs 7, 14 and 15).Declaration of InterestLlandudno Museum (supported by Conwy Culture Centre) and Amgueddfa Cymru have expressed interest in acquiring the hoard.&nbsp;AbbreviationsIARCH &ndash; Iron Age and Roman Coin Hoards project, Crisis or continuity: Hoarding in the Iron Age and Roman Britain with special reference to the third century AD.&nbsp;&nbsp;",
