    description:
      "This report will consider these coins with respect to the criteria laid down in the Treasure Act (1996):&nbsp; Namely, their age, precious metal content and whether the coins can be said to come from the same find.Circumstances of findBefore this case a total of 32 Roman silver coins have been discovered in this location. This addenda of two further coins brings the total now to 34. Of the these, Twenty Roman silver coins were found by Len Jackman between 28th January and 13th February 2019 in an area of 20-30 feet, with several being close together, indicative of a plough-scattered hoard. This case was submitted as treasure cases 2109 T157. Between the 9th and 20th of April 2022 a further 12 siliquae were found within the vicinity of these coins. This case was submitted as 2022 T386. &nbsp;Between February and March 2023 two further coins were found in this same field and will now be considered below.Description of findThe coins are both of the main silver denomination of the late Roman period, the siliqua, and both were issued by Magnus Maximus at the mint of Trier c. AD 383-8.Siliquae were among the last silver coins minted in the western Roman cities of the Roman Empire in the late fourth and early fifth century but continued to circulate after collapse of Roman rule over Britain in AD 410. Both have been clipped to remove silver from the edges of the coins, with coin 1 being more heavily reduced.Summary by mint and date:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Trier Lyon Arles Milan Aquileia Unc. TotalIssue date378/9-88&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ndash;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ndash;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ndash;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ndash;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ndash;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Total&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2From the same find?It is likely that these pieces were withdrawn from the same pool of circulation in the early fifth century AD and deposited together. The circumstances of discovery also indicate a scattered hoard.ConclusionOn the balance of probabilities, therefore, I conclude that these coins belong together as a hoard and constitute a prima facie case of Treasure by being silver coins of an antiquity greater than 300 years and of one find of more than two coins.",
