    description:
      "Description:&nbsp; A small scattered coin hoard of two Roman denarii found only one or two steps away from one another on the same day while metal detecting.The coins include:1. A silver Roman Republican coin; a denarius of the moneyer M. Porcius Laeca, dating from about 125 BC (Reece Period 1). Mint of Rome. RRC 270/1.Obverse: LAECA Helmeted head of Roma, right. Before, denominational mark (X crossed).Reverse: [M. PORC // ROMA] Libertas holding pileus and rod in a quadriga galloping right, crowned by flying Victory, left.Thickness: 1.9mm Weight: 3.17 grams Diameter: 17.2mm. Die axis:1 o&rsquo;clock.2. A Roman Republican silver denarius of Mark Antony (42-30 BC), dating to 32-31 BC (Reece period 1). Probably struck in Patrae, circa 32-31 BC. Sear (2000), p283, number 1479. RRC 544/16 The &#39;legionary&#39; coinage of Mark Antony honoured twenty three legions.Obverse: [M ANT AVG] / III VIR R P C Ship, right.Reverse: LEG III[I] Legionary eagle between two standards. TThickness: 2.0mm Weight: 3.14 grams Diameter: 17.4mm. Die axis:6 o&rsquo;clockDiscussion:&nbsp; The two coins are the same denomination but separated by almost 100 years in their date of minting. However, their close proximity may suggest these were buried at the same time. Coins of this type are known to circulate into the first and second century AD in Britain (and coins of Mark Antony have been found in third century AD hoards). There are certainly coin hoards which contain both type of coin recorded on the database such as NMS-A6F891 (2016T789) and LEIC-A67FAF (2015T457). As such there is precedent for these coins to have been deposited together.Conclusion: Each of the coins are more than 10% silver. It is probable they were deposited together as a group, deliberately or accidentally, on a single occasion in the late the 1st century BC century or later. The coins therefore fulfil the criteria of Treasure according to the terms of the Treasure Act 1996.",
