    description:
      "This report will consider these coins with respect to the criteria laid down in the Treasure Act (1996):&nbsp; Namely, their age, precious metal content and whether the coins can be said to come from the same find.Circumstances of find The 18 coins in question were found on the 7th of March 2022 by a metal-detector user. The discovery was made close to the findspot of two coin hoards found 6.5m apart (Stoke Lyne I, 2016 T753 and Stoke Lyne II, 2016 T756, PAS BERK-2C9948 and BERK-A39DED respectively) both consisting of Roman radiates. A hoard of Roman denarii from the same parish currently going through the Treasure process was not found at this location and cannot be considered a related deposit.The coinsThe coins in the hoard are all of the denomination commonly referred to as a radiate and date from the joint reign Valerian and Gallienus (AD 253-260) to the reign of the Gallic emperor Victorinus (AD 269-71). The hoard is made up of the debased copper alloy coinage issued in large quantities under the Gallic empire (AD 260-274).Summary:Radiates&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Central empireValerian and Gallienus, AD 253-260&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Salonina&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1Gallienus, &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AD 260-68&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Salonina&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1Claudius II, AD 268-70&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2Gallic empirePostumus, AD 260-9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 6Victorinus, AD 269-71&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 5Total&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 18DiscussionThe Stoke Lyne I hoard contained1691 radiates up to the reign of the Tetrici (AD 274) or later, as well as earlier coins of the rulers represented in this group. The hoard had been buried in a ceramic vessel that had been struck by the plough, scattering its contents, with only about 50% of the vessel surviving intact. Stoke Lyne II (containing 395 radiates) was of a similar date but the latest coins were of Postumus and Victorinus (as is the case in the small sample of coins listed here). It had also been contained in a vessel since broken by the plough and it is not possible to determine whether the two pots were buried at the same time or separately (the discoveries are clearly related). The catalogue for hoard II also included c. 193 stray coins from these two finds that could not be attributed to a specific hoard. It is likely that these coins are additional plough scatter from these hoards.RecommendationI conclude that these coins belong together as a hoard and constitute a prima facie case of Treasure under the Treasure Act 1996 by being bronze coins of an antiquity greater than 300 years and of one find of more than ten pieces, and as addenda to the earlier find(s) 2016 T753 and 2016 T756.",
