    description:
      "This report will consider these coins with respect to the criteria laid down in the Treasure Act (1996):&nbsp; Namely, their age, precious metal content and whether the coins can be said to come from the same find.Circumstances of findThirteen Roman silver coins were found by Len Jackman between 11th of April 2021 and the 2nd of February 2022 in an area of c.90m feet, with several being close together, indicative of a plough-scattered hoard. Three silver coins were found over a period of 4 months and reported individually to the Finds Liaison officer followed by a further 10 leading the finder to consider the case was a dispersed hoard.Description of findThe coins are all of the main silver denomination of the late Roman period, the siliqua. Siliquae were among the last silver coins minted in the western Roman cities of the Roman Empire in the late fourth and early fifth century but continued to circulate after collapse of Roman rule over Britain in AD 410. Most of the coins in the hoard appear to be very lightly clipped to remove silver from the edges of the coins. This is in keeping with the relatively early date of the hoard (tpq. c. AD 375-8).Summary by mint and date:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Trier Lyon Arles Aquileia Unc. TotalIssue date355-64&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ndash;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ndash;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ndash;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;367-75/8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ndash;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ndash;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ndash;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 10&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Total&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ndash;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 13From the same find?It is likely that these pieces were withdrawn from the same pool of circulation in the early fifth century AD and deposited together. The circumstances of discovery also indicate a scattered hoard.ConclusionOn the balance of probabilities, therefore, I conclude that these coins belong together as a hoard and constitute a prima facie case of Treasure by being silver coins of an antiquity greater than 300 years and of one find of more than two coins.",
