    description:
      "Hoard of 392 silver coins and a ceramic vessel (summary extracted from full catalogue by E. Ghey below)The coinsThe hoard consists of 374 coins (two of which plated) found in the main hoard and 18 coins (one of which plated) found in the dispersed group. The coins in the hoard are all silver Roman denarii, with the exception of one drachm of Trajan minted in Lycia. This is likely to have circulated as a denarius, being of the same superficial appearance. The earliest coins in the hoard are Republican Roman denarii issued in 32&ndash;1 BC by Mark Antony and the latest issued during the joint reign of Septimius Severus and Caracalla. The latest dated coins were issued in AD 201, though there were other more broadly dated coins of Julia Domna (traditionally dated up to AD 211) and Geta as Caesar, (dated to AD 199-204). The latest coins are unworn in appearance and are unlikely to have circulated much if at all; it is likely therefore that the hoard was deposited sometime after AD 201. A number of plated forgeries (plated coins) are present; one has a very thick layer of plated metal and it is likely that further forgeries exist in the group but cannot be determined without further analysis. The forgeries have been included in the main catalogue, noted where applicable. The presence of forgeries in the Severan circulation pool is well documented. The potteryThe pottery container requires cleaning and examination by a local expert but consists of two base sherds and 39 upper body sherds of a Roman grey-ware vessel, perhaps a small jar with pedestal base and plain rim. The sherds appear to come from the same vessel and may constitute a more or less complete pot. The external diameter of the base is 57.8mm. Traces of dark organic material (a burnt residue?) appear on the base and on the interior of some of the sherds, but there is no copper alloy staining in the vessel.",
