    description:
      "Roman coin hoard of two&nbsp;silver denarii.&nbsp;1. A&nbsp;silver Roman denarius of Elagabalus (AD&nbsp;218-222),&nbsp;dating to AD 221. Reece period 10, mint of Rome, RIC IV 45b.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Obverse description: Laureate and draped bust of Elagabalus, right, seen from rear.Obverse inscription: IMP ANTONINVS PIVS AVGReverse description: Victory flying left holding garland, flanked by shields, star in left field.Reverse inscription: &nbsp;P M TR P IIII COS III P PDiameter: 18.49&nbsp;mm; Thickness: 1.76&nbsp;mm; Weight: 2.12g&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;2. A silver Roman denarius of Vespasian (AD 69-79), dating to c.&nbsp;AD&nbsp;70-71. Reece period 4, mint of Rome. RIC&nbsp;vol. II (2nd edition) no. 46.Obverse description: Head of Vespasian, laureate, right.Obverse inscription: IMP CAES VESP AVG [PM]Reverse description: Vesta seated left holding simpulumReverse inscription: [T]RI-POT&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Diameter: 17.53&nbsp;mm; Thickness:&nbsp; 2.13&nbsp;mm; Weight: 2.64gDiscussionThe two silver denarii were found close to each other and therefore could have been deposited as part of the same find &ndash; the more worn appearance of the older coin of Vespasian may suggest a longer period of circulation. It is possible that some of the denarii from a scattered group of Roman coins reported previously as LIN-D512B7 (2019 T765) may be associated with this find, but that group considered as a whole was not suggestive of a hoard and was dispersed over a wider area.ConclusionIn conclusion, these coins constitute a prima facie case of Treasure under the Treasure Act 1996 by consisting of more than 10% precious metal content in that they are silver and is of an antiquity greater than 300 years and are of the same find.",
