    description:
      "The hoard was received in as a solid mass of coins corroded together with associated pottery, loose coins and small clusters of coins retrieved from the ploughsoil by the finder. This corroded mass had preserved the shape of its container. The pottery was friable due to conditions of preservation. The mass was 3D scanned by a third party and X-rayed at the British Museum prior to the coins being removed from the hoard, though the density of metal was too high for a good X-ray image. The decision was taken to remove the coins from the lump to aid the valuation process and because there were doubts as to its long term stability in its concreted state.The coins were removed from the lump in the Conservation department of the British Museum and cleaned in order to be identified. This was done in two main sections, with the lower and upper part of the pot, but on preliminary identification there appeared to be no significant difference between the layers in the date or type of coins, suggesting a homogenous deposit.The 268 coins recovered from the hoard are a mixture of silver denarii (the standard silver denomination from the Roman Republic to the early third century AD) and the silver coins of the later third century denomination known today as the &lsquo;radiate&rsquo;. The latter was initially introduced as a double denarius but became debased over the third century. The examples in this hoard are still of good silver content.&nbsp; This admixture of denominations is to be expected in a coin hoard of this date. The earliest coin in the hoard (a very worn denarius of Mark Antony) was over 250 years old at the time of deposition. These coins are known to have circulated for a very long time (two were found in Bag 6 of the Beau Street hoard, dated to the AD 250s (Anthony et al. eds. 2019)). The majority date from the late second to mid- third century AD, ending with the reign of Trebonianus Gallus and his son Volusian (AD 251-3). Hoards of this broad period (Reece period 12, c. AD 238-260) are less common than later third century hoards and more likely to terminate earlier, with the larger issues from the reigns of Philip and Gordian III, or later with coins of Valerian and Gallienus. They have a fairly wide distribution around Britain.",
