    description:
      "Description: Three silver denarii. The surfaces of 1 and 2 are obscured by corrosion products and coin 3 is worn, so they cannot be fully identified from photographs alone. Coins 1 and 2 appear to be first to second century denarii and coin 3 may be a Roman Republican denarius.Dimensions:Coin 1: Diameter: 17.9mm, thickness: 3.2mm, weight: 3.4gCoin 2: Diameter: 19.6mm, thickness: 3.1mm, weight: 3gCoin 3: Diameter: 17.1mm, thickness: 1.8mm, weight: 3.6gDiscussion (E. Ghey): The coins were reportedly found close together and thought to constitute a find of two or more precious coins. However, the national grid references provided were at 6 figures only and when plotted they were some distance apart. It was not possible to demonstrate that these coins were found in the same field. There is also insufficient evidence to suggest a spatial relationship with an earlier hoard of similar date from the same parish, 2004 T109, recorded on the PAS database as IARCH-68DCFA.Conclusion: The find consists of are two or more precious coins of over 300 years old and likely to contain more than 10% precious metal. However, there is insufficient evidence to suggest that they are of the same find and therefore my recommendation would be that they do not fulfil the requirements of the Treasure Act.Report by&nbsp;Lori Rogerson,&nbsp;Database Volunteer, EssexChecked by Sophie Flynn, Essex FLOAmended by Dr. Eleanor Ghey, The British Museum.",
