    description:
      "Hoard of 11 silver denarii, addendum to previous cases 2012T810&nbsp;(NMS-A00F04, 59 denarii), 2014T94&nbsp;(NMS-0F1E88, 54 denarii),&nbsp;2015T506&nbsp;(NMS-00AFB2, 26 denarii),&nbsp;2016T871&nbsp;(&nbsp;NMS-F70106, 27 denarii) and 2017T1239&nbsp;(NMS-B84D92, 13 denarii).&nbsp;The South Norfolk hoard now contains 190 coins.Catalogue:1. A complete silver denarius of the moneyer Q. Cassius Longinus dating to 55 BC (Reece Period 1). Q. CASSIVS reverse type depicting Eagle on thunderbolt right between a lituus on the left and a jug on the right. Legend below. Mint of Rome. RRC&nbsp;428/3. 3.28g.2. A complete silver denarius of the moneyer&nbsp;L. Sentius dating to the 101 BC (Reece Period 1). L. SENTI C.F. reverse type depicting Jupter in quadriga right holding thunderbolt and reins in left hand and sceptre in right. Control mark O below. Mint of Rome. RRC 325/1b. 3.38g.3.&nbsp;A complete silver denarius of the moneyers M. Aemilius Scarus and P. Plautius Hypsaeus dating to 58 BC (Reece Period 1). C HVPSAE COS /PREIVER reverse type depicting Jupiter in quadriga left holding reigns in left hand and hurling thunderbolt with right. Below horses and scorpion. Above inscription [P HVPSAE] / AED CVR. Solid border. Mint of Rome. RRC 422/1b. 3.74g.4. A complete silver denarius of the moneyer&nbsp;Mn Cordius Rufus dating to 46 BC (Reece Period 1). MN CORDIVS reverse type depicting Venus standing left holding scales in right hand and sceptre in left with Cupid perched on shoulder. Legend behind.&nbsp; RRC 463/1a. 3.74g.5. A silver denarius of Tiberius, Lyons, reverse PONTIF MAXIM type with seated female, RIC I, 30, 3.44g, AD14-37.6. A complete silver denarius of the moneyer C. Calpurnius Piso Frugi dating to 67 BC (Reece Period 1). C PISO L F FRVG[I] reverse type depicting horseman right holding whip. RRC 480/1. Obverse control mark head-dress of Isis, reverse control mark I (as BM 1904,0204.51) 3.35g.7. A complete silver denarius of the moneyer C. Considius Paetus&nbsp;dating to 46BC, Rome, reverse Victory in quadriga left. RRC&nbsp;465/4. 3.33g.8. A complete silver denarius of the moneyer P. Clodius dating to 42BC, Rome, reverse Diana standing right. RRC 494/23. 3.46g.9. A complete silver denarius of the moneyer&nbsp;L. Censorinus dating to 82BC, Rome, reverse Marsyas, RRC&nbsp;363/1. 3.39g.10. A complete silver denarius of the moneyer Mark Antony dating to the period 32-31 BC (Reece Period 1). LEG XIX reverse type depicting aquila between two standards. Inscription below. Border of dots. RRC 544/35. 3.31g.11.&nbsp;Fragment of an unknown silver denarius, uncertain type but probably Rebuplican.&nbsp;0.41g.Date: These 11 coins date from the period 101 BC to 37 AD. The latest coin in this parcel is similar to those in the rest of the hoard, suggesting deposition around the time of the Roman conquest in the early 40s AD.",
