      "Treasure Case 2019 T157. Description. A collection of 20 Roman silver siliquae, one having been snapped in half during removal from the ground. The coins were found between 28th January and 13th February 2019 in an area of 20-30 feet, with several being close together. This is strongly indicative of a plough-scattered hoard.",
    note: null,
    reasonTerm: "",
    notes:
      "Extract from full report and catalogue by E. Ghey:Description of findThe coins are all of the main silver denomination of the late Roman period, the siliqua. Siliquae were among the last silver coins minted in the western Roman cities of the Roman Empire in the late fourth and early fifth century but continued to circulate after collapse of Roman rule over Britain in AD 410. Many of them have been heavily clipped to remove silver from the edges of the coins, making them difficult to identify and suggesting a deposition date into the fifth century AD.Summary by mint and date:Issue date\t\t\tTrier\t\t\tLyon\t\t\tArles\t\t\tMilan\t\t\tAquileia\t\t\tUncertai\t\t\tTotal\t\t355-64\t\t\t0\t\t\t0\t\t\t1\t\t\t0\t\t\t0\t\t\t0\t\t\t1\t\t375-8/9\t\t\t1\t\t\t0\t\t\t0\t\t\t0\t\t\t1\t\t\t0\t\t\t2\t\t378/9-88\t\t\t5\t\t\t0\t\t\t0\t\t\t0\t\t\t0\t\t\t1\t\t\t6\t\t388-95\t\t\t2\t\t\t0\t\t\t0\t\t\t2\t\t\t0\t\t\t0\t\t\t4\t\t395-402\t\t\t0\t\t\t0\t\t\t0\t\t\t7\t\t\t0\t\t\t0\t\t\t7\t\tTotal\t\t\t8\t\t\t0\t\t\t1\t\t\t9\t\t\t1\t\t\t1\t\t\t20",
