      "DiscussionThis Theodosian nummus hoard is representative of the latest Roman assemblages of small change found on the island. Issues of the Theodosian period dominate by some 85% compared to the earlier coin types that happened to still be available in circulation.[1] Such hoards end with coins struck during the joint reign of Arcadius and Honorius, AD 395-402. RIC X dates these up to 403, the year the new college of Arcadius, Honorius and Theodosius II appear together on successor types not present here. The successor nummus type, the first of the triple reign, was the VRBS ROMA FELIX which replaced the VICTORIA AVGGG and SALVS REI PVBLICAE AE4-sized nummi of the old joint imperial college. The VRBS nummi were struck only at Rome since bronze minting had ceased north of the Alps by this point - making their chances of finding their way to Britain very slim indeed. None of the British Theodosian nummus hoards listed by RIC X or on the IARCH database contain the VRBS ROMA FELIX type, and the author of RIC X notes elsewhere that he knew of only one isolated British find near Guildford.[2]In Shiptonthorpe II, the identifiable joint reign types (i.e. with RIC X nos.) form only a small proportion - just over 5% - of the Theodosian material after the death of Magnus Maximus (i.e. AD 388-402). Interestingly, for this period the standard VICTORIA AVGGG and SALVS REI PVBLICAE types of Shiptonthorpe II are joined by a singleton of a contemporary eastern type of Flaccilla, wife of Theodosius. Overall, the impression confirmed here is that supply of nummi to Britain dried up shortly after the death of Theodosius I and the cessation of nummus production in Gaul in the second half of the AD 390s. The largest known Theodosian bronze hoard found in Britain, Caerwent I, thought to have originally contained some seven to eight thousand pieces (RBCH 1611 lists 3950 extant). However, the largest extant late nummus hoard is the more recent discovery at Bishops Cannings, Wiltshire (CHRB X, pp. 426-62): a mixed gold, silver and bronze hoard of some 7407 coins.Remains of textile bagHoard contained remains of textile, mostly wiggled threads where possibly one direction, either warp or weft, had rotted away completely. Analysis at British Museum (Caroline Cartwright) suggests remaining threads linen and, though mineralised on the outside, they retain an inner organic core. Find recovered very wet and air dried slowly. Coins initially soft and friable but toughened up on drying. Many have a fine patina, although the corrosion had unusual features. There were dense patches of very white silicates that had deposited on the bright metal before any corrosion had formed.A few unidentifiable coins and coin fragments were inaccessible for identification within the main consolidated textile mass. Although outside the scope and resources of this report, it would be an interesting future project to see if the fibres could be scientifically examined to put to test Harold Mattingly and J.W.E. Pearce&#39;s &#39;gut feeling&#39; made over seventy years ago of the similar Bermondsey Hoard:[3] &quot;Mr Pearce would prefer a more conservative date [of deposition] - c. AD 430; Mr Mattingly would be more adventurous and consider one of the AD 450 or even later.&quot;[1] Mattingly and Pearce estimated 90% for the 361-coin Bermondsey Hoard (RBCH 1561) although he could more accurately calculate at least 87% of the legible coins were Theodosian issues (NC 1947, pp.167-73). The figure for the more sizeable mixed-denomination Icklingham hoard (RBCH 1590) is 86% of the 972 nummi present and for Caerwent it is 78.5%. Note all Valentinian II entries are apportioned as Theodosian when this is not clear in older coin lists.[2] J. P. C. Kent, &#39;The Search for Fifth-Century Coins in Britain&#39;, in The Archaeological Newsletter, Dec. 1954[3] H. Mattingly and J.W.E. Pearce, &#39;The Bermondsey Hoard&#39; NC 1947, p.173.Full catalogue on file at BM",
