      "Description: Two Roman Republican silver denarii found in close association.Coin 1: Very worn and fractured Republican denarius, possibly issued by Gar[gonius], Ogul[nius] and Ver[gilius] in 86 BC (uninscribed type?). Obverse: Laureate head of Apollo right, below, thunderbolt. Reverse: Jupiter in quadriga, right; holding reins in left hand and thunderbolt in right hand. RRC 350A/2.Measurements: 18.58mm in diameter, 1.66mm thick and 3.2g in weight.Coin 2: A worn and possibly countermarked Republican denarius, possibly issued by D. Iunius Silanus c. 91BC. Obverse: Helmeted head of Roma right; behind, control mark (unclear). Reverse: [DS]ILAN[VSLF] / ROMA, Victory in biga right, holding reins in both hands; above, control mark XI[], legend in exergue below. possible I and annulet countermark below horses front legs. RRC 337/3.Measurements: 18.24mm in diameter, 1.66mm thick and 3.4g in weight.Total weight 6.6gDiscussion: This find of two Roman silver coins of the same (close) date from the same field with all probability relates to the same loss or depositional event. They are an isolated find in an area that has, to our knowledge, produced no other Roman coins or objects within 1km. Whether this is a dispersed hoard, votive deposit or purse loss it is not possible to be sure.Conclusion: It is therefore clear that these two coins date to before 1718 and as the coins are precious metal and found in close association they constitute potential Treasure under the stipulations of The Treasure Act 1996.",
