      "Summary:Denarii:Republic 30Mark Antony 5Augustus (31 BC - AD 14) 5Tiberius (AD 14?37) 1Plated ancient forgery 1Claudius (AD 41?54) 1Iron Age coins:Gallo-Belgic D quarter stater (c. 80?60 BC) 1Uninscribed British quarter stater (c. 50?20 BC) 1Stater of Cunobelin (c. AD 10?40) 1Dupondius or as: Marcus Aurelius Caesar (AD 139?161) 1Total 47The coins in the hoard are a mixture of Roman and British Iron Age coins. The majority, 35 coins, are Roman Republican silver denarii. There are 8 Roman Imperial denarii from Augustus to Claudius. The three Iron Age coins consist of two uninscribed gold quarter staters and a gold stater of Cunobelin (c. AD 10-40). The earliest coin in the hoard was a Republican Roman denarius issued in 129 BC and the latest was issued during the reign of the emperor Claudius in AD 50?54. The copper alloy dupondius or as dates to the mid second century AD and is likely to be a later stray find. Apart from this coin, the group is consistent with coinage in circulation in the immediate post-conquest period, suggesting deposition in the mid first century AD (although denarii of Mark Antony circulated for a long period and could potentially indicate a later deposition date).The Iron Age coins are of varied date but are all of types that might plausibly be found in the North Thames area in the first century AD. The uninscribed 'Pegasus' quarter stater is recorded as unique in ABC (CCI 97.2163) and placed under Kent. Sills (2017, 40 no. 72) follows this attribution and cites another unillustrated specimen, CCI 10.2782. The Kentish attribution may derive from similarity to uniface uninscribed quarter staters attributed to Dubnovellaunos (ABC 306-12) However this type is stylistically close to other Eastern British Iron Age uninscribed quarter staters, eg ABC 2362-71, Whaddon Chase staters and quarter staters and those attributed to Addedomaros , cf ABC 2526, 2529. The findspots of this specimen and the CCI examples would support such an attribution.Found with the denarii were four objects of Roman date that can be considered to be associated with the coins (identified by Philippa Walton):a) an incomplete and heavily corroded copper-alloy Colchester brooch dating to the mid first century AD. The fragment comprises the head and most of the bow. The brooch measures 34mm in length, with the head having a width of 14mm and the bow a width of 4mm.b) the foot and catchplate of a copper-alloy bow brooch dating to the first or second century AD. The foot is rectangular in plan and triangular in section with the catchplate being triangular in plan.c) an incomplete copper-alloy finger ring dating to the Roman period. The fragment comprises the shoulders and bezel of the ring. The bezel possesses an oval setting filled with degraded blue enamel. The bezel measures 14mm in width, 11mm in length and 4mm in thickness.d) a copper-alloy cruciform stud dating to the Roman period. Each arm is triangular in section and terminates in semi-circular knop which is hemispherical in section. Each knop is decorated with a groove. From the underside of the stud, there extends a central circular lug with a rounded terminal. The stud measures 26mm in width, 6mm in thickness and weighs 9.84g.",
