    description:
      "Description: The coins are all silver Roman coins of the denomination known as the denarius (plural denarii).Coin 1. Obverse: Laureate head or bust of uncertain Antonine emperor, right. Reverse: Possible standing figure (loss of surface). Damaged, missing portion of coin. Date c. 117-192 AD.Weight: 1.9g. Diameter: 17.1mm. Thickness: 2.5mm.Coin 2. Obverse: Head of uncertain (probably Flavian) emperor, right. Reverse: Illegible. Date c. 69-96 AD.Weight: 2.8g. Diameter: 18.2mm. Thickness: 2.8mm.Coin 3. Obverse: [D]IVA[&hellip;]. Bust of Faustina I, draped, right. Reverse: Illegible Uncertain standing figure. Date c. AD 141-161.Weight: 2.5g. Diameter: 18.7mm. Thickness: 2.3mm.A further coin (4, recorded as ESS-DC9FC3) was discovered in the same circumstances on 31 March 2019 and has been added to this report as an addendum. The fifth coin was found (17 October 2019 and recorded as ESS-D36CE5 (initially recorded as 2019 T1148)). These two coins are both Severan denarii, giving a tpq for the hoard as&nbsp;c. AD 194 to 198.",
