    description:
      "A hoard of Roman base silver coins: 4804 radiates and 1 denarius to AD 282.",
    note: null,
    reasonTerm: "",
    notes:
      "Harbridge, Hampshire 2017 T7Catalogue by Eleanor GheyThe bulk of the hoard was in situ in a broken container but the top had been disturbed and some coins had scattered in the surrounding soil. A plastic bag of loose coins was placed in the pot below some soil and further coins, and a small number had been coated in olive oil by the finder, which was later removed in the laboratory.Coins were removed from the pot in 8 layers each subdivided in two halves by the conservator, Saray Naidorf. The contents of each layer were sorted by emperor but no difference was found between the layers to suggest that they had been sorted or deposited at different dates. A small amount of plant material (chaff) and the remains of one insect were found associated with the coins, preserved by proximity to copper.The coinsThe coins in the hoard are all of the denomination commonly referred to as a radiate and date from the joint reign of Valerian and Gallienus (AD 253-260) to the final year of the reign of Probus (AD 276-282). The earliest coins have a higher silver content but the bulk of the hoard is made up of the debased copper alloy coinage issued in large quantities under the Gallic empire (AD 260-274). The hoard has a small number of later coins with higher silver content that post-date the coinage reform under Aurelian.Compared to other hoards of similar size and date, the Harbridge hoard has a relatively high percentage of coins of the sole reign of Gallienus (18.7%). It also has a relatively high proportion of coins of Victorinus to the Tetrici, in which it compares closely to the Aldbourne hoard (Besly 1984). This could suggest that the bulk of the hoard was formed at a relatively early date. However, unlike the Aldbourne hoard, there did not appear to be a significant variation in the proportion of these coins within the layers of the hoard itself.Associated artefactsThe coins were contained in a broken jar, although the fragments were held together with bandages to allow removal of the coins. It was associated with a vessel of 'dog bowl' form, possibly used as a lid, and a bag of associated sherds. It was not possible to comment on the fabric of these vessels due to adhering soil and examination by a local pottery specialist is recommended. The jar appears to be a grey-ware vessel with a beaded rim. The body has a wide band of diamond-shaped lattice decoration. The dog-bowl is of coarser fabric, with a black exterior and white interior. It has a flat rim and a flat base.An iron nail 20.1mm long and with a flat head 10.6mm diameter, 2.74g. The short shaft was circular in section, possibly broken. This was not diagnostic in date.Also associated with the hoard were two flint fossils, possibly belemnites, although these also have not been studied by an expert. These could be naturally occurring in a chalk soil, though it should be noted that fossils are sometimes found in special deposits dating to the Roman period. Such an association would be convincing if they were found within the hoard container but no information on their relationship was provided.Summary: (full catalogue at the British Museum)Central empireValerian and Gallienus, AD 253-260Valerian I 25Gallienus 14Salonina 33Valerian II 1Saloninus 2Diva Mariniana 1Divus Valerian II 1Gallienus, AD 260-68 825 + 1 denariusSalonina, 74Quietus 1Claudius II, AD 268-70 379Divus Claudius II 24Quintillus, AD 270 32Aurelian, AD 270-5 16 (inc. 2 pre-reform)Severina 1Tacitus, AD 275-6 31Florian, AD 276 2Probus, AD 276-282 59Gallic empirePostumus, AD 260-9 174Laelian, AD 269 3Marius, AD 269 26Victorinus, AD 269-71 1330Divus Victorinus 2Tetricus I, AD 271-4 1150Tetricus II 477Uncertain Gallic empire 58 (inc. 4 rev. brockages)Irregular 49Uncertain emperor (inc. frags) 14Total 4805",
