    notes:
      "The coins were all in a poor state of preservation (corroded or fragmentary) and many that retained their surfaces appeared to be worn smooth of most of their detail from many decades of continued circulation. The last legible sestertius was of the reign of Septimius Severus; an early obverse of Julia Domna hybridised with a reverse type proper to the Emperor coinage of AD 195. The addenda yeilded a dupondius or as of Julia Domna from roughly the same period, AD 193-8.If not stray finds, it seems possible that the few radiates represent contemporary coins with the remnants of the old sestertius circulation now kept as raw material alongside a scrapped quarter of a copper alloy disc. (At least two of the sestertii shows evidence of file marks)Associated objects submitted for examination with the coins (report by Eleanor Ghey)1. Copper alloy fragment.A fragment of sheet metal with a curved lower edge and broken top edge (across the width of the fragment). The shorter side edge is straighter with a slight inwards curve in the centre. It meets the lower edge in a rounded corner, the tip of which may be missing. The inner surface is lightly concave and the outer lightly convex. The inner surface undulates slightly with parallel ridges or striations running across the width, possibly made by gouging with a rounded object. The piece has a dark green patina with possible traces of silvering (particularly on the inner surface, which is also covered in patches of black corrosion products). The outer surface is smooth. There is no evidence of any surface decoration.Width 41.9mm, length 42.5mm. depth 26.7mm. Thickness 3.5 mm at curved outer edge and 3.2mm at break. 19.10g2. Copper alloy broochA Roman copper alloy bow-and-fantail brooch, with some elements in common with aesica and trumpet-derivative types, dating to the first to second century AD. A disc in the centre of the bow contains a four-petalled flower bordered by a circular cell filled with red enamel. A circular cell in the centre of the flower may once have contained red enamel. Where the bow meets the head of the brooch there are two empty circular cells and a triangular cell containing traces of red enamel. Above this cell and between the wings is a triangular panel containing incised lines in a herringbone pattern. The tubular wings have moulded decoration and would have held an enclosed pin; only traces of iron corrosion survive. One wing is partially broken.The brooch terminates in a fantail, the corners of which are broken. This is decorated with a crudely incised lozenge containing hatching and a hatched border, with two empty circular cells, one of which is partly missing. In the centre of the reverse of the foot is a catch-plate in the form of a lug projecting downwards with a rounded tip. The brooch has a shiny dark green patina and may be of greater antiquity than the hoard in which it was deposited.No direct parallel was found for this brooch. The form is similar to the bow-and-fantail type, some of which have a central rosette on the bow with enamel decoration (for example Hattatt 2000, 315 fig 174 no. 74), sometimes with a central stud (as in SOM-3FFAE7 with a floral motif on a flattened bow and a tubular head. Other similarly shaped brooches from the South West with such incised decoration recorded on the PAS database are DOR-5611A3 and SOM-45CCB3, the latter with a domed central boss. The latter are listed as Late Iron Age brooches by Mackreth (2011, 32 and Vol. II Plate 18, no. 6172) but are not dated. There is similarity between the incised decoration on the foot of this brooch and that of SOM-45CCB3.Length 35.5, width (head) 28.5, diameter of disc 17.9mm 18.37gReferencesMackreth, D.F. 2011. Brooches in late Iron Age and Roman Britain. Oxford and Oakville, Oxbow Books.Hattat, R. 2000. A visual catalogue of Richard Hattatt's Ancient Brooches. Oxford, Oxbow Books.",
