    description:
      "Hoard of 8 AR denarii and 14 sestertii / sestertii fractions to AD 189. A number of stray debased radiates and nummi (and a poss early modern farthing) were also recovered.Summary:Denarii:M Antony (32-31 BC), 1Otho (AD 69), 1Vespasian (AD 69-79), -Domitian Caesar, 1Trajan (AD 98-117), 2Hadrian (AD 117-38), 1Antoninus Pius (AD 138-61), 1Commodus (AD 180-92), 1; TR P XIIII = AD 188-9Sestertii and fractions:Vespasian (AD 69-79), 1 dp/as?Domitian (AD 81-96), 1 dpTrajan (AD 98-117), 1 sest?Antoninus Pius (AD 138-61), 1 sestDiva Faustina I, 2 (both sest)Marcus Aurelius (AD 161-80), 1 sestCommodus ?Caesar, 1 sestUncertain Antonine, 3 (all sest)Uncertain emperor, 3 (all dp/as)Later stray coins:Radiates, 3Nummi, 4Early modern, 1",
    note: null,
    reasonTerm: "",
    notes:
      "Also found and imaged on the PAS record (image 18) was a circular bronze object with trefoil design, 11.48g; max. diam. 30mm. X-radiography revealed the design to be openwork with three petal-shaped segments around a central pellet in an open circular frame. The oval &#39;petals&#39; contain circular cells that appear to be filled with enamel (possibly yellow in colour). This can be identified as an example of a type object of uncertain function known as a &#39;dangler&#39; (sometimes &#39;fob dangler&#39;) that dates from the late Iron Age to early Roman period. It is missing a protruding shank on the reverse - some complete examples have suspension loops attached. These artefacts may be a decorative element on horse harness or other personal equipment - earlier examples often have a triskele motif but the oval petals here seem to suggest a first to second century AD date. For similar examples on the PAS database see NCL-970F06 and YORYM-30130C.This pattern fits well with that which might be expected for a hoard of Roman coins of mixed denomination deposited early in the late second century AD. The eight later coins do not fit into the pattern of the hoard and can be considered as stray finds from the same site. The dangler is likely to be of similar date to the coins and could therefore be considered as an associated object, although this association cannot be proven in the absence of archaeological context.Recommendation on the status of TreasureOn the balance of probability, the 22 first to second century coins considered above belong together as a hoard and constitute a prima facie case of treasure by being part of a find of two or more precious metal coins of an antiquity greater than 300 years. The contemporary Roman object found in association with the coins should be likewise considered treasure.",
