    description:
      "2012 T661 South Warwickshire addendaReport to HM CoronerCircumstances of discoveryOne silver denarius was discovered on 16th August 2012 during an archaeological excavation of the site of the 2008 find of the South Warwickshire hoard (2008 T410). The coin was buried at a depth of about 10-15cm. The original find was made in a pot about 4m to the north-east of the location of this recent discovery.Four further denarii were found in September 2012 during the same archaeological investigation of the hoard site and an associated Roman period wall, at the same depth in old ploughsoil. Two were found on 3rd September and 11th September, one on 4th September, and another on 4th September.The coinsThe coins are all silver Roman coins of the denomination known as a denarius (plural denarii) (four Roman Republican (dating from 128 BC to 42 BC) and one Roman Imperial denarius of Claudius I dated to AD 50-51).",
    note: null,
    reasonTerm: "",
    notes:
      "The coins satisfy the terms of the Treasure Act with regard to age and metal content. They are certainly more than 300 years old and have a precious metal content well in excess of the 10% required.On the balance of probabilities, I conclude that they constitute a prima facie case of treasure under the terms of the Treasure Act (1996), by being part of a group of two or more precious metal coins of the same find. The coins are consistent with the type and date range of the coins in the original find and should be considered as addenda to it.",
