    description:
      "A small hoard of copper alloy Roman coins. Please see summary of Treasure report below.The coins range in date from AD 260-274 and the assemblage is broadly similar in composition to the many Romano-British coin hoards buried in the aftermath of the breakaway 'Gallic Empire'. The Gallic empire, whose capital was at the city of Trier but which had held dominion over Britain, was established in AD 260 and reconquered by the legitimate ('central') Empire in AD 274. In general, the coins were in an advanced state of corrosion; all were fragmentary to some extent and only the minority were legible:SummaryCentral EmpireGallienus (sole reign) (AD 260-8) 1Gallic EmpireVictorinus (AD 269-271) 5Tetricus I (AD 271-274) 5Tetricus II 3Uncertain Gallic (AD 269-274) 8Uncertain Emperor 7Illegible minor frags 14+Total 43Metal ContentAll the coins are of the third century AD denomination known (to modern scholarship) as a radiate, originally a silver multiple of the denarius, but by this time had become debased to the point of being essentially bronze (c.1% silver).",
