    subperiodFrom: "",
    description:
      "A small hoard of eleven Roman copper alloy coins. Please see Treasure report below for details.The coinsAll the coins are second and early third century AD brass denominations known as sestertii and have received a considerable amount of circulation wear (sing. = sestertius).The group stretches from the Emperor Hadrian (AD 117-38) to the Severan period covering the first quarter of the following century (the latest datable coin is from AD 224; the third regnal year of the emperor Severus Alexander, AD 222-35). The group can be summarised as follows:Summary:Hadrian (AD 117-38) 1Antoninus Pius (AD 138-61) 2Aurelius Caesar 1Marcus Aurelius (AD 161-80) 3Faustina II 2Wars of the Succession (AD 193-7):Julia Domna 1Severus Alexander (AD 222-235) 1 (TRP III; AD 224)Total 11Metal Content and AgeThe coins satisfy the terms of the Treasure Act with regard to age and quantity, being base metal coins over than 300 years old and more than ten pieces.Of the same find?The composition of issues and their relative degrees of circulation wear fit well with that which might be expected for a small hoard of Roman bronzes deposited in the third century AD.ConclusionOn the balance of probabilities, therefore, I conclude that these coins belong together as a hoard and constitute a prima facie case of treasure by being base-metal coins of an antiquity greater than 300 years and are of one find of more than ten pieces.",
