    notes:
      "Description of the coinsThe majority of the coins present were minted between AD 313 and 340, and are a denomination commonly known as the nummus (nummi pl.). (A small number of older coins of the later third century are also present: they represent the chance survival of an older coin type - the radiate - in the circulation.) The coins were produced at a number of mints around the empire (with an expected bias towards those within, or closest to, Britain). The final coins of the group were produced a couple of years either side of the death of Constantine the Great (AD 306-337), the first Christian Roman Emperor.No container was found with the coins but traces of textile in the corrosion product of one coin suggest they were within a sack or bag.From the same find?The coins were likely to have been in circulation at the time of burial, with the bulk of material (from the AD 330s) close to the termination date of the final coins; a typical circulation pattern. The two corroded lead tesserae (tickets or tokens of uncertain function) which were also recovered could also have formed part of the assemblage as this class of object has occasionally appeared in reports of previous Roman coin hoard finds.ConclusionOn the balance of probabilities, therefore, I conclude that these coins were buried together as a hoard and constitute a prima facie case of treasure by being bronze coins of an antiquity greater than 300 years and are of one find of more than ten pieces. The lead tesserae, by virtue of their association, should be considered likewise.Richard AbdyDept. of Coins and MedalsBritish Museum",
