    description:
      "A late Roman copper alloy nummi hoard (TBKA 'the Pewsey coin hoard') contained within a sooted grey-ware type jar. Total coins = 2384, deposited c. AD 348. Contents: Two base metal radiates and 2382 base metal nummi: Radiates: Claudius II (AD 268-70), 1; Tetricus I (AD 271-4), 1. Nummi: AD 317-24, (1 half nummus of Trier); AD 330s, (1 'Milvian Bridge' nummus fraction of Constantinople); AD 330-35, 171; AD 335-41, 911; AD 341-8, 1165; uncertain brockages, 2; uncertain/illegible, 42 (incl. 14 fused); irregular nummi 54Estimated coins: 3000. The vessel was buried in a small pit and covered with several large, roughly hewn limestone blocks. These are not local stones as the suface geology here is clay-with-flints.Sixty-nine coins or parts thereof were collected by the finder, the rest remained in the vessel. Several vessel sherd, mostly the rim and the upper part of the vessel, were also recovered by the finder. The vessel is heavily sooted, showing that it was probably used as a domestic cooking vessel prior to be used as a container for the coins. The stone covering of the hoard suggests deliberate concealment; the stones may have been a marker however it is unclear if these would have been visible or if they too were buried. The hoard was stabilised in-situ then block lifted for excavation in the lab.( During the table top excavation in the British Museum, remains of fur/hide and lead foil were found over the undisturbed upper parts of the coin hoard. Though the surface coins inside the pot had been disrupted in many places, there was enough left in situ to show that the lead foil had been laid over the coins and then, on top of that, a piece of fur/hide had been placed, hairy side down. There was no evidence that the lead foil had been wrapped around the coins or that the fur/hide was part of a bag. Both layers seem to have been used as a cap or bung, with some remaining evidence that they extended upwards, up the inside of the pot wall, rather than downwards, between the coins and the pot wall. P Pearce 24.5.2019.)Most of the pit cut had been removed however a small amount of pit fill was recovered.",
    note: null,
    reasonTerm: "",
    notes:
      "As there are more than ten copper alloy coins from the same find, and they are over 300 years old, this hoard constitutes Treasure under the stipulations of the Act.",
