      "Thirty coins are present in the group shown at the British Museum; although one is just a tiny fragment (0.28g compared to a normal weight of a whole specimen of around 2-3g). They were all silver Roman coins of the denomination known as the denarius (plural denarii), issued in the names of the emperors (and occasionally their empresses and 'Caesars', or heirs to the throne) over the course of much of the first - second centuries AD. The composition is typical of a denarius hoard buried in the early AD 160s, under the Antonine dynasty. The earliest coin was a well-worn issue of the short lived emperor Vitellius who perished in the Civil Wars of AD 69 (the 'year of the four emperors'). The latest closely dated coin is of Lucius Verus from the first year of his joint reign with the more famous emperor Marcus Aurelius: AD 161, a year with probably saw the issue of the deified Antonius Pius type also present. The lifetime issue of Marcus's wife Faustina II is less closely datable since it could have been produced up to her death in AD 176 (but does not otherwise contradict the general impression of a typical Antonine period hoard just stretching into the early years of the reign of Marcus Aurelius, AD 161-80).Full catalogue on file at British Museum",
