    description:
      "Treasure case 2012 T520: Two coins donated to the British Museum, remainder disclaimedCircumstances of findTwo groups of Roman coins were found on 21 July 2012 by three people detecting on ploughed farmland near Martock, Somerset. The finders excavated the groups at the time of finding and subsequently reported them to the Portable Antiquities Scheme. The coins (418 coins) from the two groups were bagged together and mixed before being handed in and so are catalogued together. The PAS and Somerset County Council Historic Environment Service were able to arrange re-excavation of the findspot (full report to follow). The find was reported as Treasure to HM coroner via the Portable Antiquities Scheme.The subsequent archaeological excavation recovered seven further coins (one a fragment) from the soil around the original deposition and some pottery sherds. The seven coins are all of similar types and date to the main groups and are likely to be associated. The excavation and examination of the pottery retrieved by the finders suggested the main group was contained in a ceramic jar probably covered by an upturned bowl. The top of the main group had almost certainly been hit by the plough at some point, damaging the pots and possibly scattering a few coins as well as leaving a clear plough scar in the adjacent ditch fill. The lack of a wide scatter of coins around the hoard, and the low number of broken coins, suggests the coins were mostly unaffected by this damage.The finders reported that the larger group was covered by pieces of sandstone when found, with a large piece of local blue lias adjacent. They reported that the coins were not held in the pot, which was broken, but were coming up in groups and rouleaux of 5-6 coins. The hoard or hoards had been buried within a ditch filled with occupation debris including a range of pottery. Undisturbed ditch fill between the two holes made by the finders and their report of the position of the stones, suggest the two groups of coins were originally buried separately rather than the smaller group simply being the upper part of the main group turned over by the plough. The narrow date range of all the coins does not rule out the two groups being buried at the same time and the placement certainly suggests the burial of one group was informed by the placement of the other.The coins were washed in the method recommended by the British Museum conservation department but have not undergone full mechanical cleaning and conservation. It is likely that full cleaning would allow more detailed identification of the coins and would separate some coins currently cemented together in pairs.Description of the coinsThe coins date to between AD 317-330, and the coins are a standard base metal denomination known as a nummus (pl. nummi). The coins can be grouped into two main periods: AD 317-24 was dominated by two personalities: Constantine the Great (AD 306-37) the first Christian emperor and his pagan rival Licinius (AD 308-24). Following the latter's defeat, the second period AD 324-330 falls within the reign of Constantine as sole senior emperor, together with his sons holding the rank of Caesar (junior emperors).The majority could be identified to reverse type and most could be identified to RIC number. A full catalogue is available from the Somerset FLO. Only 34 could not be identified to type and therefore dated, but the obverse styles fit within this period. The final coin was produced between AD 327 and 328. The great majority of the coins (94%) date from AD 318 to 324. The exclusion of any earlier coins is typical of hoards of this period. The absence of later types (such as the very common Gloria Exercitus with two standards) suggests that the coins were deposited before AD 330-1.Eight mints are represented: London accounts for 59% of the identifiable coins, Trier 34%. This number of London coins is an unusually high proportion for the period (compared for example to the Shrewsbury Hoard 2009 T450) and probably reflects the both the strength of this mint in the AD 317-324 period and the high number of BEATA TRANQVILLITAS types. 29% of the identified coins were Globe on Altar (BEATA TRANQVILLITAS / BEAT TRANQLITAS) designs from London, however these represented 42 different types suggesting the coins were drawn from general circulation rather than being a batch from the mint. The coins include a few bust varieties and unrecorded officinae. A summary of the coins is given below.Given the above discussion of the probability of the coins originally being buried in two groups the coins were examined to consider if their types or condition would allow the groups to be separated. The coins in general are all very good with little wear although some have copper concretions and iron pan on them from the burial environment. While some are later, the dates are continuous with no clear break into two groups and they are likely to all have circulated together.Summary (by date and mint):\t\t\tLondon\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tTrier\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tLyon\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tArles\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tRome\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tTicinum\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tAquileia\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tSiscia\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tThessal-onica\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tUncert-ain\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tTotal\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t317-324\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t192\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t99\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t11\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t2\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t3\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t5\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t54\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t367\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t324-330\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t8\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t15\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t24\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tIlleg\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t34\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t34\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tTotal\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t200\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t114\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t11\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t2\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t3\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t0\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t5\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t1\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t88\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t425\t\t\t\t\tPottery associated with the coins A full report of the pottery handed in with the coins by the finders and that retrieved by the re-excavation is available fromt he Somerset FLO. The main group of coins appear to have been buried in a Black Burnished Ware jar with a dish of similar fabric covering the top. Both are very common vessels in the area and contemporaneous with the coins. This is the same burial arrangement found in the earlier Frome Hoard. There are no vessels definitely associated with the smaller group although there is a possibility two dishes are present in sherds handed in by the finders.Other MaterialA range of iron, copper-alloy and lead items were found in the topsoil above and around the deposition point, mostly nails with one hooked fitting. They are not unambiguously Roman and cannot certainly be associated with the hoard.A farthing of Charles II was also handed in with the coins which was found in the topsoil above the hoard and is clearly not associated.Consideration as TreasureThese coins belong to a narrow period of time and form a discrete compositional group. This would suggest that they are all from one find, representing an individual's unrecovered savings deposited together as a hoard.All the coins are an argentiferous copper-alloy. However, as they are only about 5% silver or less they should be considered essentially bronze.ConclusionOn the balance of probabilities, therefore, I conclude that these coins belong together as a hoard and constitute a prima facie case of treasure by being bronze coins of an antiquity greater than 300 years and are of one find of more than ten pieces. The Roman pottery fragments by virtue of their association with the coins should be considered likewise.Richard Abdy, Dept. of Coins and Medals, British Museum, 07 January 2014Laura Burnett, Somerset FLO, November 2013",
