    description:
      "Ranging in date from AD c.270-317 the majority of coins from the group chronologically straddles the Tetrarchic period of late Roman history, from AD 294, and the midpoint in the career of the first Christian emperor Constantine the Great (AD 307-37) which would end in his achievement of absolute power over the empire.Two types of late Roman base metal denominations are present in the Claverley deposit - both representing multiples of the classical Roman currency unit, the denarius (their precise value remains subject to debate). The first coin type is the late third century radiate, so called due to the imperial effigy represented crowned by the sun's rays. The second appeared by the turn of the century, a larger denarius multiple which replaced the radiate in the fourth century, the nummus (pl. nummi).Summary:Radiates:Victorinus or Tetricus I (AD 269-4), 1Reign of Carausius (AD 286-93), 2Uncertain (270s-90s), 1Nummi by mint and period:-\t\t\tLondon\t\t\tTrier\t\t\tOthers\t\t\tUncertain\t\t\tTotal\t\tAD 294-313\t\t\t6\t\t\t3\t\t\t-\t\t\t4\t\t\t13\t\tAD 313-7\t\t\t3\t\t\t-\t\t\t1\t\t\t-\t\t\t4\t\tTotal\t\t\t9\t\t\t3\t\t\t1\t\t\t4\t\t\t17\t\tThe nummi in particular belong to a short-lived currency system and represent two stages in the decline in module of the nummus from the size of a modern two pound coin at its first incarnation, AD 294-306 to the size of a one pence piece by AD 317. In AD 318 surviving documents suggest the nummus underwent a sudden arbitrary devaluation with the resulting disruption leading to a number of coin hoards terminating in AD 317.",
