    description:
      "Circumstances: Found while searching with a metal detector between September 2009 and March 2010. The coins were found in a close area, this area had previously yielded six denarii of similar date, undoubtedly part of the same hoard (2009 T295).Description: Eleven Roman silver denarii. The earliest are two worn specimens of the second half of the first century, the others of later date, mainly belonging to the Severan dynasty. With the six earlier coins they form a discrete group in terms of date and denomination and there seems no doubt that they represent part of a dispersed hoard. The latest coin so far recovered from this area (reported under Treasure number 2009 T295) dated to 213-7, a date in accord with this group, and suggests a date of deposition in the third or fourth decade of the third century.CatalogueVitellius, RIC I, 105, 69 Vespasian, RIC II, 10, 69-71 Diva Faustina I, RIC III, 351, 141 Commodus, RIC III, 187, 189Clodius Albinus, RIC IV.1, 7, 194-5 Julia Domna, RIC IV.1, 564, 196-211Julia Domna, RIC IV.1, 572, 196-211 Julia Domna, RIC IV.1, 580, 196-211Julia Domna, RIC IV.1, 587, 196-211 Septimius Severus, RIC IV.1, 167a, 200-1Septimius Severus, RIC IV.1, 234, 210  Date: Latest coin 210 AD.Discussion: These coins are all of silver and over three hundred years in age. It seems most likely that they were deposited or lost together and thus they represent, a priori, under the stipulations of the Treasure Act 1996, a case of Treasure.Author: Adrian B. MarsdenDate: 26/8/2011",
