    description:
      "Found with the aid of a metal detector, 26.9.06 (Treasure reference 2006 T467), with a further ten coins found during subsequent archaeological investigation by Archaeology South East (Treasure case number 2008 T285).This group consists of 4653 coins made in the fourth century AD from AD 330-350. Each coin, generally known today as a nummus,is predominantly copper-alloy with a tiny admixture of silver. The legends on the reverse of the last nummi present, those of AD 348-50, invariably read FEL(ix) TEMP(orum) REPARATIO which can be translated as 'happy times are here again' ('Fel Temp' on summary). It was an optimistic hope prompted by the year 348 coinciding with the 1,100th anniversary of the traditional founding of Rome and the belief that it marked the beginning of a new age for the embattled empire. The group terminates during the joint reign of Constantius II (AD 337-61) and his younger brother Constans (AD 337-50). Both had been brought up as Christians by their father Constantine the Great (AD 306-37) the first emperor to adopt the faith. Constans was the last legitimate emperor to visit Britain.There are also coins present dating to before the joint reign of Constantius II and Constans; including issues of Constantine the Great himself, his mother St Helena and step-mother Theodora as well as another, shorter-lived, son Constantine II (d. AD 350) and a nephew Delmatius (d. AD 337). There are also over a thousand commemorative coins present celebrating the joint capitals at this time, Rome and Constantinople; produced in the AD 330s they do not bear an emperor's head. The other coins in the following summary are grouped by reverse type and then by the member of the imperial college depicted on the front of the coin. There is also a small quantity of ancient forgeries listed here as 'irregular'.Summary (including addenda coins): Early nummi, 11 AD 330s: Urbs Roma, 541 Constantinopolis, 546 + 2 add Gloria Exercitus (2 standards) (AD 330-5) Constantine I, 264 Constantine II, 311 + 1 add Constantius II, 262 Constans, 7 Uncertain emperor, 8 Gloria Exercitus (1 standard) (AD 335-40) Constantine I, 36 Constantine II Caesar, 133 Constantius II Caesar, 81 Constans Caesar, 35 Delmatius, 21 Constantine II Augustus, 20 Constantius II Augustus, 239 + 1 add Constans Augustus, 246 + 1 add Constans Caes / Aug, 4 Urbs Roma (GE1 reverse), 1 Emperor uncertain,52 Other types of AD 337-40: Divus Constantine I, 12 Helena, 152 Theodora, 50 Securitas Reip: Constantius II, 1 Constans, 1 Virtus Augusti: Constantine II, 1 Virtus Augg nn: Constantius II, 4 Constans, 1 Uncertain, 1 Victoria Augg (AD 340-8) Constans, 3 Victoria Augustorum (AD 342-3) Constans, 1 Two Victories (AD 346-8) Constantius II, 265 Constans, 1094 + 5 add Uncertain emperor, 71 Vot xx Mult xxx (AD 347-8): Constans, 1 Emperor uncertain, 1 Fel Temp coinage (AD 348-50) Constantius II, 1 Constans, 1 Uncertain brockage, Constans Augustus, 1 Irregular nummi, 53 Uncertain minor fragments 110 From the same find?Chronologically the coins belong to one coinage system and form a discrete compositional group of coins that would have been current in Britain around the middle of the fourth century AD.Itemisation of the ten copper alloy nummi of Constans and the House of Constantine, minted between AD330 and 348. These were recovered by Archaeology Southeast and attributed to the Treasure case number 2008 T285.1) Copper alloy Nummus of House of ConstantineMint unclear, 335-341ADObverse Illegible; ?laureate bust rightReverse [GLORIA EXERCITVS]; Two soldiers either side of one standard?//?Condition: extremely worn: poor2) Copper alloy Nummus of ConstansTrier, 347-8Obverse C[ONSTA]N[S P F AVG]; bust rightReverse VICT[ORIAE DD AVGGQ NN]; Two victories facing each other each holding wreath, (M)//-Condition: wornRIC VIII, p. 151, c.f. 1823) Copper alloy Nummus of ConstansTrier, 347-8Obverse CONSTANS P F AVG; bust rightReverse [VICTORIA]E DD AVGGQ NN; Two victories facing each other each holding wreath, D//[TR]SCondition: wornRIC VIII, p. 152, c.f. 195-64) Copper alloy Nummus of ConstansTrier, 347-8Obverse CONSTAN[S PF AVG]; bust rightReverse VICTOR[IAE DD AVG]G QNN; Two victories facing each other each holding wreath, D//TRSCondition: wornRIC VIII, p. 152, c.f. 195-65) Copper alloy Nummus of ConstansTrier, 347-8Obverse [CON]STANS PF AVG; bust rightReverse VICTORIAE DD AVGG [QNN]; Two victories facing each other each holding wreath, Leaf//TRSCondition: goodRIC VIII, p. 151, c.f. 185-66) Copper alloy Nummus of Constantine II as CaesarMint unclear, 330-335Obverse CONSTANTINVS IV [----]; bust rightReverse GLOR[IA EXERCI]TVS; Two soldiers standing either side of two standardsCondition: worn; poor7) Copper alloy Nummus of House of ConstantineMint unclear, 330-340Obverse CONSTAN[TINOPOLIS]; Helmeted bust leftReverse Victory on prow leftCondition: worn; poor, especially reverse8) Copper alloy Nummus of ConstansTrier, 347-8Obverse [CO]NSTAN[S PF AVG]; bust rightReverse VICTORIAE DD [AVGGQ NN; Two victories facing each other each holding wreath, M//[ ]Condition: wornRIC VIII, p. 151, c.f. 1829) Copper alloy Nummus of House of Constantine,Trier, 330-40Obverse CONSTANTINOPOLIS; Helmeted bust leftReverse Victory on prow left-//TR[ ]Condition: good10) Copper alloy Nummus of House of ConstantineMint unclear, 347-8Obverse Illegible [----]; bust rightReverse [GLORIA EX]ERC[ITVS]; Two soldiers holding one standard?//?Condition: worn",
