      "Part of Treasure Case 2009 T407: Disclaimed, returned to finder.A scattered hoard, finds so far consist of 8 fragmented Siliqua and 1 Miliarenses . Finds have been reported over three years as as 2007 T719, 2008 T743 and 2009 T407.  Further searches around the findspot have failed to identify any more coins or an obvious concentration. The fragmentary nature of all the coins retrieved suggests the hoard has been scattered and damaged by the plough with more being brought to light every year as the site is turned over by the plough.",
    note: null,
    reasonTerm: "",
    notes:
      "1. Two thirds of a silver Siliqua with concretions on each side which may be from other coins it was previously buried with. Found 08.08.2009. SUSS-C4B428.Valentinian II (375-392 AD)Mint Aquileia, 378-383 AD18.4mm in diameter by 13.4mm; 1.25g; Die Axis 6Obv. D N VA[LEN]TINI-ANVS [P F AVG]; peal diademed, draped & cuirassed bust facing rightRev. VIRTVS RO-[MANORVM]; Roma seated facing on throne, head left, holding globe & reversed spearMintmark: -//AQ[...]RIC IX, p.100, No.28c2. Half of a Silver Siliqua. Found 01.08.2009. SUSS-C48717.Theodosius I (AD 379-395)Mint Trier, 388-395 AD17.6 by 9.1mm; 0.77g; Die Axis 6Obv. [DN] THEODO-SI[VS PF AVG]; peal diademed, [draped & cuirassed bust] facing rightRev. VIRT[VS ROMANORV]M; Roma seated left on cuirass, [holding victory on globe] and reverse spearMintmark: -//TRPSRIC IX, p.31, No.94b or p.33, No.106a3. Fragment (c.) of a Silver Siliqua. Found 01.08.2009. SUSS-C4E136.House of Valentinian Mint Trier, 367-78 AD12.5 by 8.1mm; 0.44g; Die Axis 6Obv. DN VALEN[TINIANVS PF AVG]; peal diademed, [draped & cuirassed] bust facing rightRev. VRB[S ROMA]; Roma seated left [holding victory on globe and reverse spear]Mintmark: [-]//T[...]4. Fragment (c.) of a Silver Siliqua. Found 01.08.2009. SUSS-C4CC93.House of ValentinianMint Trier, 367-375 AD12.5 by 7.5mm; 0.48g; Die Axis 12Obv. [DN ... PF AV]G; [peal diademed,] draped & cuirassed bust facing rightRev. V[RBS ROMA]; Roma seated left on throne, [holding victory on globe and reverse spear]Mintmark: [-]//TRPSRIC IX, pp. 19 & 22, c.f. nos. 27/45Discussion: Part of the same hoard as 2007 T719 and 2008 T743. These fragments have been checked against the previous ones by the finder and none clearly join. Late 4th century silver coins are comparatively rare site finds in Britain. The close proximity of the findspots, along with the presence of a Miliarenses amongst the previous finds, suggests the coins were originally deposited together in a hoard or lost together, for example in a purse, and should therefore be considered as of the same find.Further searches around the findspot have failed to identify any more coins or an obvious concentration. The fragmentary nature of all the coins retrieved suggests the hoard has been scattered and damaged by the plough with more being brought to light every year as the site is turned over by the plough.As they are over 300 years old and contain over 10% precious metal they should therefore be considered Treasure within the meaning of the Treasure Act 2006.",
