    description:
      "Treasure case : 2008 T6222 AR denarii & 1441 BI radiates and associated materialThis report will consider these coins with respect to the criteria laid down in the Treasure Act (1996): Namely, their age, precious metal content and whether the coins can be said to come from the same find.The coins range in date from AD 253-296, with the exception of much earlier coins of Commodus (AD 180-92) and Severus Alexander (AD 222-35) which is are rare survivals by this period but not unheard of for hoards of this type. Many are fragmentary or otherwise in too poor a state of survival for close identification.Otherwise the group is broadly similar in composition to the many Romano-British coin hoards (at least 200 so far recorded) buried in the wake of the breakaway 'Gallic Empire'. The Gallic empire, whose capital was at the city of Trier but which had held dominion over Britain, was established in AD 260 and reconquered by the legitimate ('central') emperor Aurelian in AD 274.Summary by reign (all radiates except where noted):Central EmpireCommodus (AD 180-92), sestertius 1Severus Alexander (AD 222-235), denarius 1Valerian & Gallienus (AD 253-60)Valerian I 5Gallienus 1Salonina 2Diva Mariniana 1Gallienus & Salonina (AD 260-8)Gallienus 33Salonina 7Claudius II (AD 268-70) 32Divus Claudius 1Quintillus (AD 270) 6Aurelian (AD 270-5) 2 (but both are dated to AD 271)Gallic EmpirePostumus (AD 260-9) 40Marius (AD 269) 7Victorinus (AD 269-71) 524Tetricus I (AD 271-4) 417Tetricus II 120Britannic EmpireAllectus (AD 293-296) 1Uncertain emperor (mostly Gallic) 240 (many in fragmentary state, two fused pairs)Irregular (ancient forgeries) 2Total 1443All but the two earlier coins are of the denomination known as radiates, originally a silver multiple of the denarius, but by this time had become debased to the point of being essentially bronze (c.1% silver).Associated Pottery and other non-coin artefacts by Dr Richard HobbsDept. of Prehistory & Europe, The British MuseumA number of large and small fragments of a coarseware jar covered in soil and copper corrosion resultant from contact with the associated coins. The fabric appears to be very friable and poorly fired, and the vessel does not appear to have been wheel thrown. There are two joining parts of the base and 12 body fragments (no obvious sections of rim). There are also a large number of 'rolled' fragments of pottery; it is not clear if all or some of these are part of the vessel, although all bear traces of copper corrosion so should be considered associated; there are 25 of these fragments in a bag and around 16 loose pieces.This vessel and the associated fragments should be considered associated with the coin hoard/s.In addition, there are:- 4 pieces of natural stone;- 1 undiagnostic sherd of an orange coloured vessel;- a lump of lead, roughly rectangular, with a 'criss cross' design on its flat side;- 2 pieces of modern 'junk'.All these pieces are not associated with the coin hoard/s in my opinion.ConclusionOn the balance of probabilities, therefore, I conclude that these coins belong together as a hoard and constitute a prima facie case of treasure by being bronze coins of an antiquity greater than 300 years and are of one find of more than ten pieces. The pot and other items, except for the itemised pieces listed by Dr Hobbs, should also be considered treasure by virtue of their association with the coins.Richard Abdy and Eleanor GheyDept. of Coins and MedalsBritish Museum",
