    subperiodFrom: "",
    description:
      "TREASURE CASE : 2008 T531.75 Roman Silver, 10 Roman Bronze coins and a pot sherdAll of the coins were found within an area of 30 x 30 yards; some coins were on the surface with others at a maximum depth of nine inches. Also discovered was a whitish-grey sherd (wt. 36.96g) from the base of a small jar, which had probably once been the container for the coins. (Pots associated with coin hoards are usually buried upright - once smashed by plough activity the base of the pot stands the best chance of survival.)The coins were issued by the following Roman emperors (grouped here by joint reigns, note irregular coins are ancient forgeries):silver siliquae:AD 355-60, Constantius II & Julian Caesar & 360-3; Julian Augustus, 5 (1 x Trier, 3 x Arles, 1 x Lyon)AD 364-7, Valentinian I & Valens, 10 (2 x Arles, 6 x Lyon, 2 x Antioch)AD 367-75, Valentinian I, Valens & Gratian, 3 (all Trier)AD 375-8, Valens, Gratian, & Valentinian II, 4 (all Trier)AD 378/9-88, Gratian, Theodosius I, Valentinian II, Arcadius, Magnus Maximus & Flavius Victor, 6 (3 x Trier, 1 x Milan, 1 x Aquileia, 1 x uncertain mint)AD 388-95, Theodosius I, Valentinian II, Eugenius & Arcadius, 11 (6 x Trier, 2 x Lyon, 3 x Milan)AD 395-402, Honorius & Arcadius, 31 (all Milan)Irregular, 5base metal nummi:AD 364-78, Valentinian I (to 375), Valens, Gratian, & (from 375) Valentinian II, 6 (5 x Arles, 1 x uncertain)AD 388-95, Theodosius I, Valentinian II, Eugenius & Arcadius, 2 (1 x Arles, 1 x Lyon)Irregular, 2The coins from a fairly close-knit chronological grouping and could easily have been in circulation together before being deposited at the same time (as a hoard) in the early fifth century AD.Metal content?At this period great efforts were made by the Romans to refine gold and silver for their coinage (which carried mint-markings guaranteeing the processes) and such coins were usually as pure as was then technologically possible (greater than 95%). The nummi (singular nummus) represent the small change of the time and were essentially bronze coins.ConclusionOn the balance of probabilities, therefore, I conclude that these coins belong together as a hoard and constitute a prima facie case of treasure by being precious metal coins of an antiquity greater than 300 years and are of one find of more than two pieces. The bronze coins are treasure by being both base metal coins of the same find of ten or more pieces and also by being in association with the precious metal coins. The pot sherd should also be considered treasure by its association with the coins.",
