    subperiodFrom: "",
    description:
      "The coins All eight coins appear to be either Roman Republican or Imperial period silver denarii dating from between the first century BC and the first half of the first century AD. Only a fragment of one coin survives and they are in very worn condition, possibly burnt; it has not been possible to identify the fragment and three of the coins. The coins can be summarised as follows: 1. Denarius serratus of Q. Antonius Balbus, 82-83 BC, type RRC 364/1d (with control mark P on the reverse). 2. Denarius of C. Postumius, 74 BC, type RRC 394/1 3. Denarius of Brutus, 54 BC, type RRC 433/2 4. Denarius of Mark Antony, 32-31 BC, type RRC 544 5. Two Denarii of uncertain type and date, with head on obverse and horses / chariot on reverse, probably Roman Republican in date. 6. Denarius of uncertain type and date, head right on obverse. It is not certain whether this is a Roman Republican or Imperial denarius; the coin is too worn to identify. 7. Fragment of denarius of uncertain type and date. The same find? The coins are more or less contemporary with one another and coins of these types have previously been found together in hoards. Roman Republican coins are commonly found in hoards with early Imperial coins and a later date for one unidentified coin would therefore not alter the possibility of its association with the others. The circumstances of discovery would suggest that the coins could have been part of a scattered hoard. The later find of three coins should be considered part of the same group.",
